# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smalltalk-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smalltalk-lang/html-node-index] This document describes installing and operating the GNU Smalltalk programming environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Notable languages with OOP support include Ada, ActionScript, C++, Common Lisp, C#, Dart, Eiffel, Fortran 2003, Haxe, Java, JavaScript, Kotlin, Logo, MATLAB, Objective-C, Object Pascal, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Raku, Ruby, Scala, SIMSCRIPT, Simula, Smalltalk, Swift, Vala and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The idea of "objects" in programming began with the artificial intelligence group at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Here, "object" referred to LISP atoms with identified properties (attributes).
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Another early example was Sketchpad created by Ivan Sutherland at MIT in 1960–1961.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the glossary of his technical report, Sutherland defined terms like "object" and "instance" (with the class concept covered by "master" or "definition"), albeit specialized to graphical interaction.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Later, in 1968, AED-0, MIT's version of the ALGOL programming language, connected data structures ("plexes") and procedures, prefiguring what were later termed "messages", "methods", and "member functions".
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Topics such as data abstraction and modular programming were common points of discussion at this time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Meanwhile, in Norway, Simula was developed during the years 1961–1967.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Simula introduced essential object-oriented ideas, such as classes, inheritance, and dynamic binding.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Simula was used mainly by researchers involved with physical modelling, like the movement of ships and their content through cargo ports.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Simula is generally accepted as being the first language with the primary features and framework of an object-oriented language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Influenced by both MIT and Simula, Alan Kay began developing his own ideas in November 1966.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] He would go on to create Smalltalk, an influential OOP language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] By 1967, Kay was already using the term "object-oriented programming" in conversation.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Although sometimes called the "father" of OOP, Kay has said his ideas differ from how OOP is commonly understood, and has implied that the computer science establishment did not adopt his notion.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] A 1976 MIT memo co-authored by Barbara Liskov lists Simula 67, CLU, and Alphard as object-oriented languages, but does not mention Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the 1970s, the first version of the Smalltalk programming language was developed at Xerox PARC by Alan Kay, Dan Ingalls and Adele Goldberg.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk-72 was notable for use of objects at the language level and its graphical development environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk was a fully dynamic system, allowing users to create and modify classes as they worked.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Much of the theory of OOP was developed in the context of Smalltalk, for example multiple inheritance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the late 1970s and 1980s, OOP rose to prominence.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The Flavors object-oriented Lisp was developed starting 1979, introducing multiple inheritance and mixins.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In August 1981, Byte Magazine highlighted Smalltalk and OOP, introducing these ideas to a wide audience.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] LOOPS, the object system for Interlisp-D, was influenced by Smalltalk and Flavors, and a paper about it was published in 1982.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In 1986, the first *Conference on Object-Oriented Programming, Systems, Languages, and Applications* (OOPSLA) was attended by 1,000 people.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This conference marked the start of efforts to consolidate Lisp object systems, eventually resulting in the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the 1980s, there were a few attempts to design processor architectures that included hardware support for objects in memory, but these were not successful.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Examples include the Intel iAPX 432 and the Linn Smart Rekursiv.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the mid-1980s, new object-oriented languages like Objective-C, C++, and the Eiffel language emerged.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Objective-C was developed by Brad Cox, who had used Smalltalk at ITT Inc.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup created C++ based on his experience using Simula for his PhD thesis.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer produced the first design of the Eiffel language in 1985, which focused on software quality using a design by contract approach.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the 1990s, OOP became the main way of programming, especially as more languages supported it.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] These included Visual FoxPro 3.0, C++, and Delphi.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] OOP became even more popular with the rise of graphical user interfaces, which used objects for buttons, menus and other elements.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] One well-known example is Apple's Cocoa framework, used on macOS and written in Objective-C.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] OOP toolkits also enhanced the popularity of event-driven programming.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] At ETH Zürich, Niklaus Wirth and his colleagues created new approaches to OOP.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Modula-2 (1978) and Oberon (1987), included a distinctive approach to object orientation, classes, and type checking across module boundaries.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is not obvious in Wirth's design since his nomenclature looks in the opposite direction: It is called type extension and the viewpoint is from the parent down to the inheritor.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages that were initially developed before OOP was popular have been augmented with object-oriented features, including Ada, BASIC, Fortran, Pascal, and COBOL.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The OOP features provided by languages vary.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Below are some common features of OOP languages.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Comparing OOP with other styles, like relational programming, is difficult because there isn't a clear, agreed-upon definition of OOP.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages, like Java, provide information hiding via visibility key words (`private` and `public`).
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some languages like Python don't provide a visibility feature, but developers might follow a convention such as starting a private member name with an underscore.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Intermediate levels of access also exist, such as Java's `protected` keyword, (which allows access from the same class and its subclasses, but not objects of a different class), and the `internal` keyword in C#, Swift, and Kotlin, which restricts access to files within the same module.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Supporters of information hiding and data abstraction say it makes code easier to reuse and intuitively represents real-world situations.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] However, others argue that OOP does not enhance readability or modularity.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Raymond has written that OOP languages tend to encourage thickly layered programs that destroy transparency.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Raymond compares this unfavourably to the approach taken with Unix and the C language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] SOLID includes the open/closed principle, which says that classes and functions should be "open for extension, but closed for modification".
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli has stated that OOP languages have "extremely poor modularity properties with respect to class extension and modification", and tend to be extremely complex.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Leo Brodie says that information hiding can lead to duplicate code, which goes against the don't repeat yourself rule of software development.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance can be supported via the class or the prototype, which have differences but use similar terms like object and instance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In class-based programming, the most common type of OOP, an object is an instance of a class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The class defines the data (variables) and methods (logic).
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] An object is created via the constructor.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Every instance of the class has the same set of variables and methods.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Classes may inherit from other classes, creating a hierarchy of classes: a case of a subclass inheriting from a super-class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` class might inherit from a `Person` class which endows the Employee object with the variables from `Person`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The subclass may add variables and methods that do not affect the super-class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Most languages also allow the subclass to override super-class methods.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some languages support multiple inheritance, where a class can inherit from more than one class, and other languages similarly support mixins or traits.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, a mixin called UnicodeConversionMixin might add a method unicode_to_ascii() to both a FileReader and a WebPageScraper class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] An abstract class cannot be directly instantiated as an object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Other classes are utility classes which contain only class variables and methods and are not meant to be instantiated or subclassed.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Instead of providing a class concept, in prototype-based programming, an object is linked to another object, called its *prototype* or *parent*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In Self, an object may have multiple or no parents, but in the most popular prototype-based language, JavaScript, an object has exactly one prototype link, up to the base object whose prototype is null.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] A prototype acts as a model for new objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, if you have an object `fruit`, you can make two objects `apple` and `orange` that share traits of the `fruit` prototype.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Prototype-based languages also allow objects to have their own unique properties, so the `apple` object might have an attribute `sugar_content`, while the `orange` or `fruit` objects do not.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In all OOP languages, via object composition, an object can contain other objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` object might contain an `Address` object, along with other information like `name` and `position`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Composition is a "has-a" relationships, like "an employee has an address".
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some languages, like Go, don't support inheritance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Instead, they encourage "composition over inheritance", where objects are built using smaller parts instead of parent-child relationships.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, instead of inheriting from class Person, the Employee class could simply contain a Person object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This lets the Employee class control how much of Person it exposes to other parts of the program.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Delegation is another language feature that can be used as an alternative to inheritance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Programmers have different opinions on inheritance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup, author of C++, has stated that it is possible to do OOP without inheritance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Rob Pike has criticized inheritance for creating complex hierarchies instead of simpler solutions.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] People often think that if one class inherits from another, it means the subclass "is a" more specific version of the original class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This presumes the program semantics are that objects from the subclass can always replace objects from the original class without problems.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This concept is known as behavioral subtyping, more specifically the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] However, this is often not true, especially in programming languages that allow mutable objects, objects that change after they are created.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In fact, subtype polymorphism as enforced by the type checker in OOP languages cannot guarantee behavioral subtyping in most if not all contexts.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, the circle-ellipse problem is notoriously difficult to handle using OOP's concept of inheritance.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Behavioral subtyping is undecidable in general, so it cannot be easily implemented by a compiler.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Because of this, programmers must carefully design class hierarchies to avoid mistakes that the programming language itself cannot catch.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] A method may be invoked via dynamic dispatch such that the method is selected at runtime instead of compile time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] If the method choice depends on more than one type of object (such as other objects passed as parameters), it's called multiple dispatch.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In this context, a method call is also known as message passing, meaning the method name and its inputs are like a message sent to the object for it to act on.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Dynamic dispatch works together with inheritance: if an object doesn't have the requested method, it looks up to its parent class (delegation), and continues up the chain to find a matching method.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Polymorphism in OOP refers to subtyping or subtype polymorphism, where a function can work with a specific interface and thus manipulate entities of different classes in a uniform manner.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, imagine a program has two shapes: a circle and a square.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Both come from a common class called "Shape." Each shape has its own way of drawing itself.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] With subtype polymorphism, the program doesn't need to know the type of each shape, and can simply call the "Draw" method for each shape.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The programming language runtime will ensure the correct version of the "Draw" method runs for each shape.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Because the details of each shape are handled inside their own classes, this makes the code simpler and more organized, enabling strong separation of concerns.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] An object's methods can access the object's data.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages use a special word, like `this` or `self`, to refer to the current object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In languages that support open recursion, a method in an object can call other methods in the same object, including itself, using this special word.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This allows a method in one class to call another method defined later in a subclass, a feature known as late binding.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Design patterns are common solutions to problems in software design.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some design patterns are especially useful for OOP, and design patterns are typically introduced in an OOP context.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Sometimes, objects represent real-world things and processes in digital form.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, a graphics program may have objects such as `circle`, `square`, and `menu`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] An online shopping system might have objects such as `shopping cart`, `customer`, and `product`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Niklaus Wirth said, "This paradigm [OOP] closely reflects the structure of systems in the real world and is therefore well suited to model complex systems with complex behavior".
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] However, more often, objects represent abstract entities, like an open file or a unit converter.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Not everyone agrees that OOP makes it easy to copy the real world exactly or that doing so is even necessary.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Bob Martin suggests that because classes are software, their relationships don't match the real-world relationships they represent.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer argues that a program is not a model of the world but a model of some part of the world; "Reality is a cousin twice removed".
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Steve Yegge noted that natural languages lack the OOP approach of naming a thing (object) before an action (method), as opposed to functional programming which does the reverse.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This can make an OOP solution more complex than one written via procedural programming.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] The following are notable software design patterns for OOP objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] A common anti-pattern is the God object, an object that knows or does too much.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Both OOP and relational database management systems (RDBMSs) are widely used in software today.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] However, relational databases don't store objects directly, which creates a challenge when using them together.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This issue is called object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] To solve this problem, developers use different methods, but none of them are perfect.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] One of the most common solutions is object-relational mapping (ORM), which helps connect object-oriented programs to relational databases.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Examples of ORM tools include Visual FoxPro, Java Data Objects, and Ruby on Rails ActiveRecord.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some databases, called object databases, are designed to work with OOP.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] However, they have not been as popular or successful as relational databases.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Date and Darwen have proposed a theoretical foundation that uses OOP as a kind of customizable type system to support RDBMSs, but it forbids objects containing pointers to other objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In responsibility-driven design, classes are built around what they need to do and the information they share, in the form of a contract.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] This is different from data-driven design, where classes are built based on the data they need to store.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] According to Wirfs-Brock and Wilkerson, the originators of responsibility-driven design, responsibility-driven design is the better approach.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have tried to formally define the semantics of OOP.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance presents difficulties, particularly with the interactions between open recursion and encapsulated state.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have used recursive types and co-algebraic data types to incorporate essential features of OOP.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Abadi and Cardelli defined several extensions of System F<: that deal with mutable objects, allowing both subtype polymorphism and parametric polymorphism (generics), and were able to formally model many OOP concepts and constructs.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Although far from trivial, static analysis of object-oriented programming languages such as Java is a mature field, with several commercial tools.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Many popular programming languages, like C++, Java, and Python, use OOP.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] In the past, OOP was widely accepted, but recently, some programmers have criticized it and prefer functional programming instead.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] A study by Potok et al. found no major difference in productivity between OOP and procedural programming.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Some believe that OOP places too much focus on using objects rather than on algorithms and data structures.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] For example, programmer Rob Pike pointed out that OOP can make programmers think more about type hierarchy than composition.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] He has called OOP "the Roman numerals of computing".
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Rich Hickey, creator of Clojure, described OOP as overly simplistic, especially when it comes to representing real-world things that change over time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Alexander Stepanov said that OOP tries to fit everything into a single type, which can be limiting.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] He argued that sometimes we need multisorted algebras: families of interfaces that span multiple types, such as in generic programming.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Stepanov also said that calling everything an "object" doesn't add much understanding.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] OOP was created to make code easier to reuse and maintain.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] However, it was not designed to clearly show the flow of a program's instructions.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] As computers began using more parallel processing and multiple threads, it became more important to understand and control how instructions flow.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Paul Graham believes big companies like OOP because it helps manage large teams of average programmers.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] He argues that OOP adds structure, making it harder for one person to make serious mistakes, but at the same time restrains smart programmers.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Raymond, a Unix programmer and open-source software advocate, argues that OOP is not the best way to write programs.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Richard Feldman says that, while OOP features helped some languages stay organized, their popularity comes from other reasons.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Lawrence Krubner argues that OOP doesn't offer special advantages compared to other styles, like functional programming, and can complicate coding.
[src:smalltalk-lang/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli says that OOP is slower and takes longer to compile than procedural programming.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo is shipped with source code compiled into a *system image* that contains all software needed to run Pharo.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Like the original Smalltalk-80, Pharo provides several live programming features such as immediate object manipulation, live updates, and just-in-time compilation (JIT).
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The system image includes an integrated development environment (IDE) to modify its components.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo was forked from Squeak v3.9 in March 2008.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo is a pure object-oriented, dynamically typed, and reflective language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The stated project goal is to revisit Smalltalk design and enhance it.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The name Pharo comes from the French word "phare" (French pronunciation: [faʁ]) which means lighthouse.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] This is why the Pharo logo shows a drawing of a lighthouse inside the final letter *O* of the name.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo is based on general concepts of Smalltalk but seeks to improve on them, so does not limit itself to them.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The basic syntax of the language has a close resemblance to Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] However, the way classes are defined in Pharo differs from other Smalltalk dialects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The Pharo syntax is based on Smalltalk-80 language syntax with several extensions.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Some of these are common among modern Smalltalk dialects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The Pharo language syntax is supposed to be very simple and minimalist.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The basic language elements are often presented on one postcard as a showcase for the language's brevity.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The language grammar does not specify directly how the code should be stored in files.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo uses Tonel as the preferred code serializing format.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo emerged as a fork of Squeak, an open-source Smalltalk environment created by the original Smalltalk-80 team (Dan Ingalls and Alan Kay).
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] It focuses on modern software engineering and development techniques.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo is supported by the Pharo consortium (for legal entities) [2] and the Pharo association for physical persons [3].
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Some companies use Pharo for their development projects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The Pharo consortium was created for companies wishing to support the Pharo project.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] The Pharo association was created in 2011 for users wishing to support the project.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Pharo relies on a virtual machine that is written almost entirely in Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] Beginning in 2008, a new virtual machine (Cog) for Squeak, Pharo and Newspeak has been developed that performs nearly as well as the fastest Smalltalk virtual machine.
[src:smalltalk-lang/pharo] In 2014/2015 the VM community is working on Spur, a new Memory Manager for Cog that should again increase performance and provide better 64-bit VM support.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In Smalltalk, executing programs are built of opaque, atomic *objects*, which are instances of template code stored in classes.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] These objects intercommunicate by passing of messages, via an intermediary virtual machine environment (VM).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A relatively small number of objects, called primitives, are not amenable to live redefinition, sometimes being defined independently of the Smalltalk programming environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Having undergone significant industry development toward other uses, including business and database functions, Smalltalk is still in use today.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] When first publicly released, Smalltalk-80 presented numerous foundational ideas for the nascent field of object-oriented programming.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Since inception, the language provided interactive programming via an integrated development environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This requires reflection and late binding in the language execution of code.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Later development has led to at least one instance of Smalltalk execution environment which lacks such an integrated graphical user interface or front-end.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-like languages are in active development and have gathered communities of users around them.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] American National Standards Institute (ANSI) Smalltalk was ratified in 1998 and represents the standard version of Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk took second place for "most loved programming language" in the Stack Overflow Developer Survey in 2017, but it was not among the 26 most loved programming languages of the 2018 survey.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] There are a large number of Smalltalk variants.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The unqualified word *Smalltalk* is often used to indicate the Smalltalk-80 language and compatible VM, the first version to be made publicly available and created in 1980.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The first hardware-environments which ran the Smalltalk VMs were Xerox Alto computers.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk was the product of research led by Alan Kay at Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC); Alan Kay designed most of the early Smalltalk versions, Adele Goldberg wrote most of the documentation, and Dan Ingalls implemented most of the early versions.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-71 was an unpublished language design by Kay (circa 1971).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In September 1972, Kay made a bet that the core of a programming language based on the idea of message passing could be implemented in "a page of code"; by about the eighth morning, a working interpreter scheme had emerged, forming the basis for what is now termed Smalltalk-72.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Its syntax and execution model were very different from modern Smalltalk variants.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The first Smalltalk interpreter actually implemented was for Smalltalk-72, and was written by Dan Ingalls in about 700 lines of BASIC in October 1972 for the Data General Nova.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This version was demonstrated at the MIT AI Lab by Alan Kay in November that year; published accounts of the Actor model cite this period and Smalltalk-72's message-passing ideas as an influence on the model's development.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The first bitmap line drawing routines were implemented by Ted Kaehler in late December 1972.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-72 was ported to the Xerox Alto in April 1973, the same month the first units began operation.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] After significant revisions which froze some aspects of execution semantics to gain performance (by adopting a Simula-like class inheritance model of execution), Smalltalk-76 was created.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This system had a development environment featuring most of the now-familiar tools, including a class library code browser/editor.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-80 added metaclasses, to help maintain the "everything is an object" (except variables) paradigm by associating properties and behavior with individual classes, and even primitives such as integer and Boolean values (for example, to support different ways to create instances).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-80 was the first language variant made available outside of PARC.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In 1981, it was shared with Tektronix, Hewlett-Packard, Apple Computer, and DEC for review and debugging on their platforms.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The August 1981 issue of *Byte* magazine was devoted to Smalltalk-80 and brought its ideas to a large audience.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Several books on Smalltalk-80 were also published.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-80 became the basis for all future commercial versions of Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The final release of Smalltalk-80 Version 1 was in November 1981.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Xerox only distributed Version 1 to Apple, DEC, HP, and Tektronix, but these companies were allowed unrestricted redistribution via any system they built.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This encouraged the wide spread of Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Later, in 1983, Xerox released Smalltalk-80 Version 2.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This version was generally available to the public, although under a restrictive license.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Versions 1 and 2 were fairly similar, although Version 2 did have some added features such as a spelling corrector.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Each release consisted of a virtual image (platform-independent file with object definitions) and a virtual machine specification.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] ANSI Smalltalk has been the standard language reference since 1998.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Two currently popular Smalltalk implementation variants are descendants of those original Smalltalk-80 images.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Squeak is an open source implementation derived from Smalltalk-80 Version 1 by way of Apple Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] VisualWorks is derived from Smalltalk-80 version 2 by way of Smalltalk-80 2.5 and ObjectWorks (both products of ParcPlace Systems, a Xerox PARC spin-off company formed to bring Smalltalk to the market).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] As an interesting link between generations, in 2001, Vassili Bykov implemented Hobbes, a virtual machine running Smalltalk-80 inside VisualWorks.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] During the late 1980s to mid-1990s, Smalltalk environments, including support, training and add-ons, were sold by two competing organizations: ParcPlace Systems and Digitalk, both California-based.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] ParcPlace Systems tended to focus on the Unix/Sun microsystems market, while Digitalk focused on Intel-based PCs running Microsoft Windows or IBM's OS/2.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Both firms struggled to take Smalltalk mainstream due to Smalltalk's substantial memory needs, limited run-time performance, and initial lack of supported connectivity to SQL-based relational database servers.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] While the high price of ParcPlace Smalltalk limited its market penetration to mid-sized and large commercial organizations, the Digitalk products initially tried to reach a wider audience with a lower price.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] IBM initially supported the Digitalk product, but then entered the market with a Smalltalk product in 1995 named VisualAge/Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Easel introduced Enfin at this time on Windows and OS/2.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Enfin became far more popular in Europe, as IBM introduced it into IT shops before their development of IBM Smalltalk (later VisualAge).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Enfin was later acquired by Cincom Systems, and is now sold under the name ObjectStudio, and is part of the Cincom Smalltalk product suite.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In 1995, ParcPlace and Digitalk merged into ParcPlace-Digitalk and then rebranded in 1997 as ObjectShare, located in Irvine, California.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] ObjectShare (NASDAQ: OBJS) was traded publicly until 1999, when it was delisted and dissolved.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The merged firm never managed to find an effective response to Java as to market positioning, and by 1997 its owners were looking to sell the business.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In 1999, Seagull Software acquired the ObjectShare Java development lab (including the original Smalltalk/V and Visual Smalltalk development team), and still owns VisualSmalltalk, although worldwide distribution rights for the Smalltalk product remained with ObjectShare who then sold them to Cincom.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] VisualWorks was sold to Cincom and is now part of Cincom Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Cincom has backed Smalltalk strongly, releasing multiple new versions of VisualWorks and ObjectStudio each year since 1999.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Cincom, GemTalk, and Instantiations, continue to sell Smalltalk environments.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] IBM ended VisualAge Smalltalk, having in the late 1990s decided to back Java instead and, as of 2005, is supported by Instantiations, Inc.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Instantiations renamed the product VA Smalltalk (VAST Platform) and continue to release new versions yearly.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] GNU Smalltalk is a free software implementation of a derivative of Smalltalk-80 from the GNU project.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Pharo Smalltalk is a fork of Squeak oriented toward research and use in commercial environments.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] As of 2016, a significant development that has spread across all Smalltalk environments is the increasing usage of two web frameworks, Seaside and AIDA/Web, to simplify the building of complex web applications.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Seaside has seen considerable market interest with Cincom, Gemstone, and Instantiations incorporating and extending it.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk was one of many object-oriented programming languages based on Simula.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk is also one of the most influential programming languages.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Virtually all of the object-oriented languages that came after—Flavors, CLOS, Objective-C, Java, Python, Ruby, and many others—were influenced by Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk was also one of the most popular languages for agile software development methods, rapid application development (RAD) or prototyping, and software design patterns.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The highly productive environment provided by Smalltalk platforms made them ideal for rapid, iterative development.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk emerged from a larger program of Advanced Research Projects Agency-funded research that in many ways defined the modern world of computing.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In addition to Smalltalk, working prototypes of things such as hypertext, GUIs, multimedia, the mouse, telepresence, and the Internet were developed by ARPA researchers in the 1960s.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Alan Kay (one of the inventors of Smalltalk) also described a tablet computer he named the Dynabook which resembles modern tablet computers.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk environments were often the first to develop what are now common object-oriented software design patterns.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] One of the most popular is the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern for user interface design.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The MVC pattern enables developers to have multiple consistent views of the same underlying data.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] It's ideal for software development environments, where there are various views (e.g., entity-relation, dataflow, object model, etc.) of the same underlying specification.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Also, for simulations or games where the underlying model may be viewed from various angles and levels of abstraction.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In addition to the MVC pattern, the Smalltalk language and environment were influential in the history of the graphical user interface (GUI) and the *what you see is what you get* (WYSIWYG) user interface, font editors, and desktop metaphors for UI design.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The powerful built-in debugging and object inspection tools that came with Smalltalk environments set the standard for all the integrated development environments, starting with Lisp Machine environments, that came after.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk uses several collection filter operators that rhyme with the "-ect" suffix, collect:, select:, inject:into:, et al.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] As in other object-oriented languages, the central concept in Smalltalk-80 (but not in Smalltalk-72) is that of an *object*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] An object is always an *instance* of a *class*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Classes are "blueprints" that describe the properties and behavior of their instances.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] For example, a GUI's window class might declare that windows have properties such as the label, the position and whether the window is visible or not.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The class might also declare that instances support operations such as opening, closing, moving and hiding.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Each particular window object would have its own values of those properties, and each of them would be able to perform operations defined by its class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Receive a message from itself or another object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In the course of processing a message, send messages to itself or another object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The state an object holds is always private to that object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Other objects can query or change that state only by sending requests (messages) to the object to do so.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Any message can be sent to any object: when a message is received, the receiver determines whether that message is appropriate.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] If the message is not understood by the object then the virtual machine sends the *doesNotUnderstand:* message with the original message as an argument.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The default implementation of doesNotUnderstand: raises an exception that, if not caught, opens the system's debugger.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Unlike most other languages, Smalltalk code can be modified while the system is running.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Live coding and applying fixes 'on-the-fly' is a dominant programming methodology for Smalltalk and is one of the main reasons for its productivity.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk is a "pure" object-oriented programming language, meaning that, unlike C++ and Java, there are no primitive types.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] All values are represented as objects and computation on integers uses message sending just like any other object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In Smalltalk, types such as integers, Booleans and characters are also objects, in the sense that they are instances of corresponding classes, and operations on them are invoked by sending messages.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The transition from small to large integers is transparent to the programmer; variables do not require type declarations.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This makes the system both concise and flexible.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A programmer can change or extend (through subclassing) the classes that implement what in other languages would be primitive values, so that new behavior can be defined for their instances—for example, to implement new control structures—or even so that their existing behavior will be changed.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This fact is summarized in the commonly-heard phrase "In Smalltalk everything is an object", which may be more accurately expressed as "all values are objects", as variables are not.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Since all values are objects, classes are also objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Each class is an instance of the *metaclass* of that class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Metaclasses in turn are also objects, and are all instances of a class named Metaclass.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Classes contain method dictionaries that map selectors (the equivalent of function procedure names in other languages) to method objects, objects that are executed to evaluate messages.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Classes inherit from other classes, with either Object or ProtoObject at the root of the class hierarchy.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Sending a message to an object at the most abstract involves fetching the class of the receiver (the object being sent the message) and looking up the message's selector in the class's method dictionary, followed by the superclass and so on until the method is found or doesNotUnderstand is sent.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk virtual machines use various techniques to speed up message lookup so the system provides both a simple consistent message binding mechanism and good efficiency.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Code blocks—Smalltalk's way of expressing anonymous functions—are also objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] They have a very lightweight syntax and are used throughout the system to implement control structures, especially for the Collection hierarchy.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Reflection is a feature of having a meta-model as Smalltalk does.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-80 is a totally reflective system.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-80 provides both structural and computational reflection.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk is a structurally reflective system which structure is defined by Smalltalk-80 objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The classes and methods that define the system are also objects and fully part of the system that they help define.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The Smalltalk compiler, which is itself written in Smalltalk and exists alongside all the other code in the system, compiles textual source code into method objects, typically instances of `CompiledMethod`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] These get added to classes by storing them in a class' method dictionary.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The part of the class hierarchy that defines classes can add new classes to the system.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The system is extended by running Smalltalk-80 code that creates or defines classes and methods.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In this way a Smalltalk-80 system is a "living" system, carrying around the ability to extend itself at run time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] One can even extend the compiler at run-time; indeed this is how the compiler is developed and maintained.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Since the classes are objects, they can be asked questions such as "what methods do you implement?" or "what fields/slots/instance variables do you define?".
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] So objects can easily be inspected, copied, (de)serialized and so on with generic code that applies to any object in the system.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk-80 also provides computational reflection, the ability to observe the computational state of the system.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In languages derived from the original Smalltalk-80 the current activation of a method is accessible as an object named via a pseudo-variable (one of the six reserved words), `thisContext`, which corresponds to a stack frame in conventional language implementations, and is called a "context".
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Sending a message is done within some context, and to evaluate the message another context is created, the first being the sender of the former.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In this way the stack is a linked list of context objects, and the debugger is essentially an inspector of this spaghetti stack.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] By sending messages to `thisContext` a method activation can ask questions like "who sent this message to me".
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] These facilities make it possible to implement coroutines or Prolog-like back-tracking without modifying the virtual machine.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The exception system is implemented using this facility.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] One of the more interesting uses of this is in the Seaside web framework which relieves the programmer of dealing with the complexity of a web browser's back button by storing continuations for each edited page and switching between them as the user navigates a web site.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Programming the web server using Seaside can then be done using a more conventional programming style.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] As with message sending Smalltalk-80 virtual machines optimize away the expensive use of contexts internally, providing the illusion and flexibility of a spaghetti stack without most its costs.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Essentially, context objects are created lazily as required, for example when a message is sent to the thisContext variable.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] An example of how Smalltalk can use reflection is the mechanism for handling errors.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] When an object is sent a message that it does not implement, the virtual machine sends the object the `doesNotUnderstand:` message with a reification of the message as an argument.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The message (another object, an instance of `Message`) contains the selector of the message and an `Array` of its arguments.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In an interactive Smalltalk system the default implementation of `doesNotUnderstand:` is one that opens an error window (a notifier) reporting the error to the user.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Through this and the reflective facilities the user can examine the context in which the error occurred, redefine the offending code, and continue, all within the system, using Smalltalk-80's reflective facilities.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] By creating a class that understands (implements) only doesNotUnderstand:, one can create an instance that can intercept any message sent to it via its doesNotUnderstand: method.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Such instances are called transparent proxies.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Such proxies can then be used to implement a number of facilities such as distributed Smalltalk where messages are exchanged between multiple Smalltalk systems, database interfaces where objects are transparently faulted out of a database, promises, etc.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The design of distributed Smalltalk influenced such systems as CORBA.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The following examples illustrate the most common objects which can be written as literal values in Smalltalk-80 methods.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The following list illustrates some of the possibilities for numbers.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The last two entries are a binary and a hexadecimal number, respectively.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The number before the 'r' is the radix or base.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The base does not have to be a power of two; for example 36rSMALLTALK is a valid number equal to 80738163270632 decimal.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Two equal strings (strings are equal if they contain all the same characters) can be different objects residing in different places in memory.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In addition to strings, Smalltalk has a class of character sequence objects named *Symbol*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Symbols are guaranteed to be unique—there can be no two equal symbols which are different objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Because of that, symbols are very cheap to compare and are often used for language artifacts such as message selectors (see below).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Symbols are written as # followed by a string literal.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] defines a seven element array whose first element is a literal array, second element a byte array, third element the string 'four', and so on.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Blocks are explained in detail further in the text.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Many Smalltalk dialects implement additional syntaxes for other objects, but the ones above are the essentials supported by all.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The two kinds of variables commonly used in Smalltalk are instance variables and temporary variables.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Other variables and related terminology depend on the particular implementation.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] For example, VisualWorks has class shared variables and namespace shared variables, while Squeak and many other implementations have class variables, pool variables and global variables.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Temporary variable declarations in Smalltalk are variables declared inside a method (see below).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] They are declared at the top of the method as names separated by spaces and enclosed by vertical bars.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] declares a temporary variable named index which contains initially the value `nil`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] declares two variables: index and vowels.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Variables are initialized to nil except the indexed variables of strings, which are initialized to the null character or ByteArrays which are initialized to 0.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A variable is assigned a value via the '`:=`' syntax.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Assigns the string `'aeiou'` to the formerly declared vowels variable.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The string is an object (a sequence of characters between single quotes is the syntax for literal strings), created by the compiler at compile time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In the original Parc Place image, the glyph of the underscore character ⟨_⟩ appeared as a left-facing arrow ⟨←⟩ (like in the 1963 version of the ASCII code).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk originally accepted this left-arrow as the only assignment operator.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Some modern code still contains what appear to be underscores acting as assignments, harkening back to this original usage.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Most modern Smalltalk implementations accept either the underscore or the colon-equals syntax.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The message is the most fundamental language construct in Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Even control structures are implemented as message sends.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk adopts by default a dynamic dispatch and single dispatch strategy (as opposed to multiple dispatch, used by some other object-oriented languages).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Unary messages have higher precedence than binary messages, which have higher precedence than keyword messages, and evaluation is strictly left-to-right.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In this situation 42 is called the message *receiver*, while 'factorial' is the message *selector*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The receiver responds to the message by returning a value (presumably in this case the factorial of 42).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] "factorial" above is what is called a *unary message* because only one object, the receiver, is involved.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In this expression two objects are involved: 2 as the receiver and 4 as the message argument.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The message result, or in Smalltalk parlance, *the answer* is supposed to be 16.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Such messages are called *keyword messages*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] which answers the index of character 'o' in the receiver string, starting the search from index 6.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The selector of this message is "indexOf:startingAt:", consisting of two pieces, or *keywords*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Such interleaving of keywords and arguments is meant to improve readability of code, since arguments are explained by their preceding keywords.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The receiver in this case is "Rectangle", a class, and the answer will be a new instance of the class with the specified width and height.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Finally, most of the special (non-alphabetic) characters can be used as what are called *binary messages*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] which sends the message "+" to the receiver 3 with 4 passed as the argument (the answer of which will be 7).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] is the message ">" sent to 3 with argument 4 (the answer of which will be false).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The programmer is free to define new binary selectors just as they are free to define novel unary and keyword messages.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Notice that the Smalltalk-80 language itself does not imply the meaning of those operators.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The outcome of the above is only defined by how the receiver of the message (in this case a Number instance) responds to messages "+" and ">".
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A side effect of this mechanism is operator overloading.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A message ">" can also be understood by other objects, allowing the use of expressions of the form "a > b" to compare them.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Smalltalk is an expression-based language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Every statement, including control constructs, has a value, which is some object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] An expression can include multiple message sends.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In this case expressions are parsed according to a simple order of precedence.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Unary messages have the highest precedence, followed by binary messages, followed by keyword messages.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The answer of the last message sent is the result of the entire expression.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Parentheses can alter the order of evaluation when needed.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] will change the meaning so that the expression first computes "3 factorial + 4" yielding 10.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] That 10 then receives the second "factorial" message, yielding 3628800.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] 3628800 then receives "between:and:", answering false.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Because the meaning of binary messages is not coded into Smalltalk-80 syntax, all of them are considered to have equal precedence and are evaluated simply from left to right.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] which sends "factorial" to 3, then "factorial" to the result (6), then "log" to the result (720), producing the result 2.85733.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A series of expressions can be written as in the following (hypothetical) example, each separated by a period (period is a statement separator, not a statement terminator).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This example first creates a new instance of class Window, stores it in a variable, and then sends two messages to it.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This rewrite of the earlier example as a single expression avoids the need to store the new window in a temporary variable.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] According to the usual precedence rules, the unary message "new" is sent first, and then "label:" and "open" are sent to the receiver of "new".
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A block of code (an anonymous function) can be expressed as a literal value (which is an object, since all values are objects).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Where *:params* is the list of parameters the code can take.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The resulting block object can form a closure: it can access the variables of its enclosing lexical scopes at any time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Blocks can be executed by sending them the *value* message.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Compound variations exist to provide parameters to the block e.g., `value:value:` and `valueWithArguments:`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The literal representation of blocks was an innovation which on the one hand allowed certain code to be significantly more readable; it allowed algorithms involving iteration to be coded in a clear and concise way.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Code that would typically be written with loops in some languages can be written concisely in Smalltalk using blocks, sometimes in a single line.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] But more importantly blocks allow control structure to be expressed using messages and polymorphism, since blocks defer computation and polymorphism can be used to select alternatives.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] This is related to functional programming, wherein patterns of computation (here selection) are abstracted into higher-order functions.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] For example, the message *select:* on a Collection is equivalent to the higher-order function filter on an appropriate functor.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Control structures do not have special syntax in Smalltalk.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] They are instead implemented as messages sent to objects.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] For example, conditional execution is implemented by sending the message ifTrue: to a Boolean object, passing as an argument the block of code to be executed if and only if the Boolean receiver is true.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The two subclasses of Boolean both implement ifTrue:, where the implementation in subclass True always evaluates the block and the implementation in subclass False never evaluates the block.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Blocks are also used to implement user-defined control structures, enumerators, visitors, exception handling, pluggable behavior and many other patterns.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In the last line, the string is sent the message select: with an argument that is a code block literal.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The code block literal will be used as a predicate function that should answer true if and only if an element of the String should be included in the Collection of characters that satisfy the test represented by the code block that is the argument to the "select:" message.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] A String object responds to the "select:" message by iterating through its members (by sending itself the message "do:"), evaluating the selection block ("aBlock") once with each character it contains as the argument.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] When evaluated (by being sent the message "value: each"), the selection block (referenced by the parameter "aBlock", and defined by the block literal "[:aCharacter | aCharacter isVowel]"), answers a Boolean, which is then sent "ifTrue:".
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] If the Boolean is the object true, the character is added to a string to be returned.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The exception handler's "ex" argument provides access to the state of the suspended operation (stack frame, line-number, receiver and arguments etc.) and is also used to control how the computation is to proceed (by sending one of "ex proceed", "ex reject", "ex restart" or "ex return").
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Often, most of this definition will be filled in by the environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Notice that this is a message to the `Object` class to create a subclass named `MessagePublisher`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] In other words: classes are first-class objects in Smalltalk which can receive messages just like any other object and can be created dynamically at execution time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] When an object receives a message, a method matching the message name is invoked.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The following code defines a method publish, and so defines what will happen when this object receives the 'publish' message.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The method's name is `#quadMultiply:and:`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] The return value is specified with the `^` operator.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] Objects are responsible for determining dynamically at runtime which method to execute in response to a message—while in many languages this may be (sometimes, or even always) determined statically at compile time.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p01] creates (and returns) a new instance of the MessagePublisher class.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Smalltalk is one of the first systems to be based around an Integrated Development Environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] There are a rich variety of tools to support code development, and other activities, such as graphics, and music.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Smalltalk was the first system in which the modern desktop paradigm of Windows, Icons, Menus, and Pointers (WIMP) was created.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Although pointers had already been invented, Smalltalk was the first system to implement overlapping windows and pop-up menus.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] While there are several programming tools we shall describe the following five major tools.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Smalltalk-80 derived systems organize classes within "system categories", such as `Kernel-Numbers`, `Kernel-Objects`, `Collections-Abstract`, `Collections-Sequenceable`, etc, and within classes methods are organized in named categories such as `accessing`, `arithmetic`, `instance creation`, etc.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] When one of the selectors in the fourth pane is selected the source for that method is displayed in the fifth pane.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] If only a category is selected and not a method, the fifth pane shows a template for defining a new method.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] If a system category is selected but no class, a template for creating a class in the category is displayed.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Various pop-up menus allow one to query the tool such as searching for a class by name, finding all senders of a selected message, or all implementors of the message, and so on.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] In this way the browser is both a code reading and system exploration tool and a code authoring tool.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] A Workspace is a simple text editor editing a single string.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] One can type arbitrary text in the workspace, including Smalltalk expressions.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Both workspaces and the browser's text panes are typically syntax highlighted.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] By using blocks to separate different expressions one can have several syntax highlighted expressions, each with their own temporaries in a single workspace.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The Transcript is a special workspace associated with the global Transcript.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] There are various inspectors, some tailored to displaying different kinds of object.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] To the left is a list of the object itself (with the label "self"), followed by the instance variables in the object, which will include numbered instance variables in sequences such as strings and arrays.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Selecting a name in the list replaces the workspace's contents with a print string of the selected variable.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Editing and "accepting" the text in the workspace pane when an instance variable is selected will assign the result of the evaluation to the selected variable.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] One can "drill down" by using the "inspect" command on the list menu which will apply to the selected instance variable.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] More sophisticated inspectors (e.g. explorers) support finder-like tree access so that object structure can be traversed without opening additional windows.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The default response to an unhandled exception is to open a Notifier, which is a window containing a stack backtrace of the first few activations, and buttons such as "Debug", "Proceed", "Close", etc.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] If the programmer chooses "Debug" then the full debugger opens.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] At the top is the stack window, containing a list of the contexts in the stack.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Selecting a context causes the middle pane to display the text of the context's method, and to highlight the current expression within the method.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Selecting the top context will display the method raising the exception and the message raising the exception will be highlighted.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Selecting a context causes the bottom four panes to be updated.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The bottom left two panes are the receiver inspector, that inspect the receiver of the selected message.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The bottom right two panes are the context inspector that show the argument and temporary variable names in the selected context and allow display and modification of these variables.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Sending the message `self halt` causes an exception which opens a notifier, providing a simple breakpoint facility (typically breakpoint facilities provide more than just the simple halt, but it was the first such facility).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Workspaces also provide a "debug it" evaluator which opens a debugger on the selected expression positioned at the first message send within the expression.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] So selecting `52 factorial` and choosing "debug it" from the pop-up menu opens a debugger with the "doit context" selected and the `factorial` selector highlighted.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The debugger provides buttons to do "step into", "step over", etc.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Hence by choosing "step into" one can explore the evaluation of `52 factorial`.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] In this way the debugger provides an inspector of a process, allowing one to explore a halted computation.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] If an exception results from a doesNotUnderstand:, or subclassResponsibility send, then the notifier will include a "Create" button, allowing the programmer to choose where in the receiver's hierarchy to define an "initial draft" of the method to be implemented.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Redefining a method in the debugger causes the selected context to reset back to the first statement (arguments are not modifiable in Smalltalk so this gets the execution state back to the start of a method).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] In this way the debugger supports live programming, defining methods as the computation proceeds.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] This is an extremely productive and enjoyable way to program.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Everything in the system is at your finger tips.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] One has the full power of workspaces to evaluate subexpressions, and the browser to search for supporting code as one programs.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Clicking on the Debug button opens the Notifier into a Debugger allowing inspecting the call stack and editing and continuing from any method activation.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] In this case the Notifier has created a template of the missing method that the programmer can edit, compile, and then continue the computation.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The Hello world program is used by virtually all texts to new programming languages as the first program learned to show the most basic syntax and environment of the language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] For Smalltalk, the program is extremely simple to write.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The following code, the message "show:" is sent to the object "Transcript" with the String literal 'Hello, world!' as its argument.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Invocation of the "show:" method causes the characters of its argument (the String literal 'Hello, world!') to be displayed in the transcript ("terminal") window.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] To see the results of this example, a Transcript window must be open.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Most popular programming systems separate static program code (in the form of class definitions, functions or procedures) from dynamic, or run time, program state (such as objects or other forms of program data).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] They load program code when a program starts, and any prior program state must be recreated explicitly from configuration files or other data sources.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Any settings the program (and programmer) does not explicitly save must be set up again for each restart.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] A traditional program also loses much useful document information each time a program saves a file, quits, and reloads.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] This loses details such as undo history or cursor position.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Image based systems don't force losing all that just because a computer is turned off, or an OS updates.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Many Smalltalk systems, however, do not differentiate between program data (objects) and code (classes).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Thus, most Smalltalk systems store the entire program state (including both Class and non-Class objects) in an image file.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The image can then be loaded by the Smalltalk virtual machine to restore a Smalltalk-like system to a prior state.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] This was inspired by FLEX, a language created by Alan Kay and described in his M.Sc. thesis.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Smalltalk images are similar to (restartable) core dumps and can provide the same functionality as core dumps, such as delayed or remote debugging with full access to the program state at the time of error.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Other languages that model application code as a form of data, such as Lisp, often use image-based persistence as well (see EMACS, for example).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] This method of persistence is powerful for rapid development because all the development information (e.g. parse trees of the program) is saved which facilitates debugging.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] However, it also has serious drawbacks as a true persistence mechanism.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] For one thing, developers may often want to hide implementation details and not make them available in a run time environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] For reasons of legality and maintenance, allowing anyone to modify a program at run time inevitably introduces complexity and potential errors that would not be possible with a compiled system that exposes no source code in the run time environment.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Also, while the persistence mechanism is easy to use, it lacks the true persistence abilities needed for most multi-user systems.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The most obvious is the ability to do transactions with multiple users accessing the same database in parallel.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Everything in Smalltalk-80, unless customised to avoid the possibility, is available for modification from within a running program.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] This means that, for example, the IDE can be changed in a running system without restarting it.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] In some implementations, the syntax of the language or the garbage collection implementation can also be changed on the fly.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Even the statement `true become: false` is valid in Smalltalk, although executing it is not recommended except for demonstration purposes (see virtual machine, image-based persistence, and backups).
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] Smalltalk programs are usually compiled to bytecode, which is then interpreted by a virtual machine or dynamically translated into native machine-code.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The results of previous message lookups are cached in self-modifying machine-code resulting in very high-performance sends that can out-perform the indirect function calls in C++ virtual method calls.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] OpenSmalltalk VM (**OS VM**) is a relatively high-performance implementation of the Smalltalk virtual machine on which several modern open-source Smalltalk dialects are based.
[src:smalltalk-lang/smalltalk-80-p02] The OS VM derives from the original Back-to-the-Future (BTTF) Squeak interpreter implemented by Dan Ingalls, Ted Khaeler, John Maloney and many other contributors.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Squeak runs on a stack virtual machine (VM), allowing for a high degree of portability.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] The Squeak system includes code for generating a new version of the VM on which it runs, along with a VM simulator written in Squeak.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Dan Ingalls, an important contributor to the Squeak project, wrote the paper upon which Squeak is built, and constructed the architecture for five generations of the Smalltalk language.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Alan Kay is an important contributor to the Squeak project, and Squeak incorporates many elements of his proposed Dynabook concept.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Many Squeak contributors collaborate on Open Cobalt, a free and open source virtual world browser and construction toolkit built on Squeak.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] The first version of Scratch was implemented in Squeak.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] OpenQwaq, a virtual conferencing and collaboration system, is based on Squeak.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Squeak is also used in the Nintendo ES operating system.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Squeak 4.0 and later may be downloaded at no cost, including source code, as a prebuilt virtual machine image licensed under the MIT License, with the exception of some of the original Apple code, which is governed by the Apache License.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] Squeak was originally released by Apple under its own *Squeak License*.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] While source code was available and modification permitted, the Squeak License contained an indemnity clause that prevented it from qualifying as true free and open-source software.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] First, in May, Apple used its own Apple Public Source License, which satisfies the Free Software Foundation's concept of a Free Software License and has attained official approval from the Open Source Initiative as an Open Source License.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] However, The Apple Public Source License fails to conform to the Debian Free Software Guidelines.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] To enable inclusion of Etoys in the One Laptop Per Child project, a second relicensing was undertaken using the Apache License.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] At this point, an effort was also made to address the issue of code contributed by members of the Squeak community, which it was not in Apple's power to unilaterally relicense.
[src:smalltalk-lang/squeak] For each contribution made under the Squeak License since 1996, a relicensing statement was obtained authorizing distribution under the MIT license, and finally in March 2010, the result was released as Squeak 4.0, now under combined MIT and Apache licenses.
